  Summary: RelationshipMetadata TypedDict

  What was done:

  1. Created RelationshipMetadata TypedDict in /core/services/protocols/base_protocols.py:
    - total=False makes all fields optional (relationships have heterogeneous properties)
    - Covers ~80% of common relationship properties:
        - Core metrics: confidence, strength
      - Timestamps: created_at, updated_at (ISO strings)
      - Domain-specific strengths: alignment_score, contribution_score, enablement_strength, etc.
      - Type categorizations: contribution_type, dependency_type, support_type
  2. Updated get_relationship_metadata return type:
    - Protocol: ResultType[dict[str, Any] | None] → ResultType[RelationshipMetadata | None]
    - Implementation: Added cast with explanatory comment
  3. Exported from core/services/protocols/__init__.py

  Benefits:

  - IDE autocomplete for common relationship properties
  - Type-safe access to confidence, strength, created_at, etc.
  - Extensible: Additional properties are still accessible via dict access (TypedDict is structural)
  - No breaking changes: Existing code continues to work

  Design trade-off:

  As noted in your original analysis, this is a lightweight approach that provides type safety for common fields (~80% of use cases) while avoiding the complexity of:
  - Union types for all metadata variants
  - Generic R type parameter on BackendOperations
  - Separate TypedDict per relationship type

